that whenever we encountered something,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
or, you know, we've also seen other people, you know,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
run into things,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
that those issues are very often resolved very quickly.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
So a few words about the client, right?

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
Because we work at this consultancy, Xomnia,

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
and Thijs and I, we were both placed at the same client,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
in the same team, Alleyander.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
So let me share you,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.000
let me share a few things about our project,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:12.000
and about Alleyander.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Alleyander provides electricity.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.000
It's the largest utilities company in the Netherlands, right?

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
Even also here in Amsterdam.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And yeah, these numbers should give you an idea of the size, right?

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.000
And what matters is that number, 35,000 networks.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
That will come back in a moment.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Because that influences the amount of computations we have to do,

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
or that our code has to do.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And Alleyander has a problem,

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
just like all the other utilities companies in the Netherlands.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Red, red is bad.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Red is bad.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:59.000
Red means that there is no more capacity to add things like heat pumps,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.000
or charging stations, or solar panels.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:07.000
And for us consumers, it's not so much a problem just yet,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.000
but on the commercial side of things, the commercial connection,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:14.000
very often Alleyander just has to deny them.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.000
Sorry, our network cannot handle whatever it is you want.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
So they're being waitlisted.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And so Alleyander has this huge task

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
that they need to reinforce their entire network.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Yeah, that means digging up cables, replacing them,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:35.000
installing additional transformers.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
You can imagine that this is a very costly and time-consuming endeavor.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And what they want to do is they want to go from a reactive approach

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
to a proactive approach,

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
so that before problems actually start to arise,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
based on our predictions, they can say,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.000
you know what, let's take on this particular network

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
in this particular neighborhood.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Let's reinforce that network so that we can accept more connections,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
more heat pumps, solar panels, and what have you.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
That's what we were developing, this tool called Delphi.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
We're looking here at the street level,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:18.000
and those colors are predicted by our software.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Again, red is bad.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
So the before situation, what were we dealing with?

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Processing just a single network.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
Remember, Alleyander has over 35,000 networks.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.000
Processing just one of them takes over five hours.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And part of this calculation is a simulation

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
where we need to produce samples.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
And ideally, we want to produce 50 of them,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
but the current code base only allowed for 25.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So we were already limited right there.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:04.000
This was being run on a beefy machine, again on Amazon, on AWS.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
The process used over 500 gigs of RAM, just a single ETL process.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:17.000
So then, all of a sudden, upper management came down,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
and they said to us, guys, we have this great idea.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
Instead of running this calculation once per year,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
let's do it once per month.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And instead of computing it for a handful of networks,

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:33.000
let's do our entire grid, 35,000 networks.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And you know what? You have 5,000 bucks a month to do this.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.000
We're like, wow, yeah, that's a great idea.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
But how are we going to do this?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
You know, Thijs and I, of course,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
we immediately knew what the answer was going to be.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Can anyone guess?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Polars, that's right.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
It's just that we were part of a bigger team,

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and we still had to convince the rest.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And yeah, imagine this, right?

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
It's a team of, what, six, seven people,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
and three of those people came from Xomnia.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And here we come.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
We go and we say, you know what?

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.000
You know what we should use?

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
We should use this product called Polars

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
that we have developed in-house.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:24.000
We should rewrite our entire code base with this.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
So you can imagine that a couple of, or that the others,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
the ones actually working for Alejandro full-time,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
that they were a little bit skeptic,

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:38.000
and not so eager, nor lazy.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
That was a joke.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
You know, to accept this, yeah?

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
So we had to convince them.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:48.000
So it didn't help.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
We were, of course, very proud that Polars came from Xomnia.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
But in this case, it was working against us.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
It also didn't help that Polars wasn't well-known back then.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
We're talking almost two years ago, yeah?

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And yeah, this was pre-version 1.0.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
So what did we do?

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
We showed them the numbers, right?

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
We needed to convince them with actual results.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.000
So what did we do?

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:20.000
We took out a small piece of Pandas code, right,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
and translated that to Polars.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:24.000
Not one-to-one.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:30.000
You cannot translate Pandas to Polars line-by-line, right?

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
It's the same as translating English to Dutch word-for-word, right?

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
It doesn't put any sods on the dike, right?

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
But by...

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.000
Yeah, it takes...

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:46.000
Thank you, Rico.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:47.000
This is being recorded,

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:53.000
so you can always watch back if you want to really get the joke.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:57.000
So this is a matter of examining the inputs,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:58.000
examining the outputs,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
and then reasoning, you know,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
how can we accomplish this using Polars, right?

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
It requires a different way of thinking.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.000
No more brackets.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
No more indices.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And so, yeah, what we had, yeah, Panda,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
I can go into the details afterwards if you're interested,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
but what matters is the result.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:26.000
We went from a thing that took 30 seconds to, you know,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
a new thing that did the same thing,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
which only took about a second,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:32.000
and that really convinced them.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:40.000
So that's our very first lesson of today is show, don't tell.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And now I'll give the floor to my co-author,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
former colleague, and current friend,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
to tell you about, you know,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:50.000
some other lessons that we've learned along the way.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:51.000
By the way, here's the code,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:52.000
the code that we actually produced.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Doesn't it look beautiful?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
Yeah, right.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
Thanks for passing the torch.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
Yeah, so I'll take you along in this journey about all the things

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:09.000
that we've learned during this project as we went along it.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:13.000
So the lesson number one that I can share with everyone,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
benchmark all the time.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Literally after every step, run a benchmark,

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
see what the improvements are because this allows to be guided

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.000
towards what actually makes an impact, right?

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:31.000
One of the things that we ultimately didn't do well enough was to do

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
all these benchmarks to keep track of which changes were making

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:35.000
the difference.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.000
So we had to dig in some of the CloudWatch logs,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:43.000
had to dig up down in the commit history to start rerunning things

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
from way back before we started implementing things.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And that way we were able to come up with all the differences

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
and put numbers to all the improvements we made overall.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So this is one of the things that we did in the beginning,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:59.000
just a very small network that we were able to run locally because,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
or I think on AppStream machines, just like a smaller machine,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
had like a peak usage of about, was it 37 gigabytes of RAM?

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And this is just one sample, just a very small example,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
just to see what kind of difference we made.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
And after all these changes that we made,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
we were able to reduce that to about a third

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
for just this small example.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
And this already allows us to actually go to management and show like,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
hey, this is the difference we're making.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
It's hard to convince management, like, yeah,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
the code is going to do exactly the same thing.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:31.000
There's no new features.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:32.000
Please let us do it.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
It never sits that well.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
They want features, not the same thing.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
But if you start putting numbers to it,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:42.000
that's already a lot more convincing than not having any of that

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
to back it up.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
On a bigger example, this is one of the examples we had

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
where we needed the 500 gigabyte instances for.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
So this is something you see like building up.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:58.000
Also had to do with the type of architecture we were using in the code.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
This, before we came in and before we started using AWS,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
there was this massive on-premise server that you could just claim

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
for yourself and just crunch the numbers over the weekend.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
So it was never that big of a deal.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:13.000
But as we moved to AWS and you pay for what you use,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
obviously it became bigger of a deal.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:23.000
So the before picture, this is one of the jobs we found is 465 gigabytes.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
And afterwards, you can see that in a more iterative manner,

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:30.000
we designed the code differently with the help of Polars,

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
and now it's only using 75 gigabytes of RAM.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So for exactly the same type of job, that's a big improvement.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And also one of the things that you can't quite see in here

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
is that we're able to do twice the amount of samples,

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
which was not something possible before,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
because as you can see, it's ramping up.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Then you start needing to pull out bigger and bigger instances,

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
so it already took long enough like this.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:56.000
This is what we got back to.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:01.000
So with the benchmarks, the questions you can answer is like

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
you can drill down into what exact changes make the difference,

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
and you can put numbers to the business impact

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.000
to share with your stakeholders what you're up to.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And one of the things I didn't talk about yet

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
is how it can prevent regressions.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
So while writing the book,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
I was benchmarking different versions of Polars

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
with the benchmarking tool, the PDSH,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.000
and we noticed that somewhere along version 1.2,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:35.000
some regression crept in for a very specific set of queries.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
And this is also by benchmarking often,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
you can find these kinds of regressions,

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
especially if you're translating code to different ways

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:45.000
of doing things to translating it from Pandas to Polar,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
from R to Python in the first place.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
There's always a risk that you just tweak something the wrong way,

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
you just hit something you didn't intend to.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
And by benchmarking often, you can catch these things quickly

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
and prevent them from happening

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
and preventing from building on top of that.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Ultimately, this regression is also something

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
that was already fixed by the time we had found it, funny enough.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.000
But it was also by refactor, everything was fixed again,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:12.000
so Polars is very, very fast still.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
Brings me to the second lesson.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Work lazy, not hard.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
I bet in a room full of programmers,

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
that's something that will resonate.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
So we're in the beginning to understand Polars better.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
We started working with the more eager ways,

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
but lazy makes a big difference.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
As Orsan already explained why,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
this is one of the differences you can see,

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
so it's the same type of benchmark.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Again, with the log scale, you can see that even Polars,

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
compared to itself, makes a massive jump in performance

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
when you see the lazy engine compared to the eager,

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
and that's just because a lot of work doesn't have to be done.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.000
So work lazy, not hard.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
Another thing that we learned is,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:57.000
so with this lesson of having put everything into the lazy mode,

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
we just try to run the whole query that we have on our program,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
we try to just make it lazy entirely.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:07.000
But that's also not the optimal way to do things.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
There's like a golden middle road in there,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
where some stages need to be kind of like,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:16.000
you would call it cached or persisted,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
depending on what framework you're working with.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
For example, Polars itself already does some caching in here.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
So if you have two subqueries that are running,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
and they're using the same frame

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
that's resulting from another part of the query,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
it will be cached, and both of these branches in the tree

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
can read from that cache.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
But this gets kind of hairy the moment you start running

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:46.000
gigantic queries in programs that have a massive pipeline.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
The problem is that it starts having to keep all kinds of things in RAM,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
it starts blowing up, it starts getting bloated,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:54.000
it just grinds to a halt.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
So one of the tricks is one of the most simple diagrams

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
we've added to the book.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
Literally the conversion between a data frame and a lazy frame

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:05.000
can be done with these two methods.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.000
So parts of the query that we ran,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
we just collected them on the spot.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
Just save it to RAM for now,

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
and from there you can reuse that frame,

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
which you just keep in RAM until it's not needed anymore,

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
and you start building more lazy queries on top of that.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
So one example of that would be,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
you're going to need a little bit of imagination

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:27.000
to keep it possible to do on a slide.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
So you take a lazy frame,

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
say you have some heavy computation

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
that you need to apply to that.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:36.000
In this case, with every collect,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
you run the lazy frame query all the way from scratch.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
So that means that this heavy computation that's in there

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
is being run twice, which is a waste.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
So instead, you can kind of cache it like this.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.000
So you just run this heavy computation once,

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
you cache it to RAM,

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
and from there these two calculations that are following

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
are just taking that from the sub-result,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.000
from the intermittent stage from RAM.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:04.000
One of the things we learned to love,

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
as we came for all the performance,

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
the promised performance improvements of Polars, of course,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
but one of the things we came to love

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
is the consistency that Polars offers.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:19.000
So I'm not sure if you guys worked with strings in Pandas.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.000
Luckily, the Arrow backend improved a lot of things,

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
but back when they still had NumPy,

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
there was all these different types

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
that you could use for string.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:31.000
So in the beginning, it was just a Python object

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
that was stored in the frame.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
Later, they came with an extension type,

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
which was the StringD type,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
and there's also the Arrow StringD type,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.000
which also ties into this,

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.000
and Polars is just string, as you would expect.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
On top of that, Polars also doesn't use the index,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:51.000
which is something that's almost...

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
I'm kind of scared to call out index

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
in a room full of Polar users,

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:59.000
but an index, or even worse, a multi-index,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
brings all kinds of unintended behavior with it.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
So you can get all kinds of unexpected nonce

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.000
or incorrect joins that you hadn't expected,

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
and it reduces your flexibility by a lot.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
So especially with reshaping or filtering,

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:16.000
you often have to reset or re-index your frame,

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
which is kind of something you don't really want to think about

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
if you're just working on your data frame.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:22.000
So one of the things we could just completely drop

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.000
is the reset index drop-through.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:30.000
So I'm curious if you guys can think for yourself,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
like, if you have this operation,

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:37.000
if you see this, what do you expect the outcome to be?

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:47.000
Because sort values sorts on the index as well,

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
you still get the same result.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:51.000
So this is effectively a non-op.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.000
Yeah, that's not what you expect it to be.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
If you say, like, hey, give me this column and sort the values,

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.000
you want that column but sorted,

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
and instead it just doesn't do that.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:04.000
All kinds of stuff like this, Polars just doesn't do it.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
On top of that, also, I'm not sure

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:10.000
if you worked with missing values in Pandas.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.000
Yeah, so I made this table

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
with an overview of different types of data,

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
and it shows the preferred way of showing

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.000
the missing value for those data types.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Now, recently, the Pandas NA got introduced,

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
which already made it a bit better.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.000
But still, for numerics, it's none,

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:31.000
even though, according to the standards,

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.000
that's not a number.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
It means that the operation that you did

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:37.000
was on numerical data, but resulted in something

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:39.000
that can't be represented as a number.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:43.000
But it's not missing, so it doesn't quite match.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
Same thing with datetimes.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.000
You get, like, not a time.

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:50.000
So there's a lot of stuff going on here.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Ultimately, in Polars, it's just a non-value

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:55.000
if it's missing.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.000
So you have all the missing data in Polars

00:23:58.000 --> 00:23:59.000
can be represented with a null,

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
and every data type supports it.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.000
And even under the engine,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:08.000
it's optimized to deal with these null values.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:12.000
Missing data will never convert the datatype

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:13.000
to something else.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
This is something that, especially,

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:17.000
like some of the datatypes in Pandas

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.000
had the problem that the moment you want to include

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.000
an actual null, that you had to convert it

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:22.000
to something else.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:23.000
Especially floats didn't support nulls,

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.000
so then you would have to start working with objects

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:27.000
to kind of get around that.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:29.000
But it's all suboptimal.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:32.000
So ultimately, it boiled down to NAN is not a missing value,

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:33.000
but the result of an invalid operation,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:39.000
and Polars just supports that as it should.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:41.000
So back to the converting of the database.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:44.000
Like, if you have a 20,000-line database,

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:45.000
you're not going to get that done

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
in one sprint of two weeks.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:50.000
So the way we try to do this is by taking baby steps.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:52.000
We just took the parts of the program

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.000
that we knew were taking the longest time

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
to run in Pandas, and that's where we started.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:00.000
So this requires that you're able

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.000
to only work on small parts of your program.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
It's relatively easy.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:08.000
So if you want to go from Pandas to Polars,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
you just throw your Pandas data frame

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:12.000
in the Polars data frame constructor,

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.000
and you can start working your Polars magic on it.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:16.000
And ultimately, at the end of the part

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
you want to work on,

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
you just go back to it by calling toPandas,

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
and you get a Pandas frame back.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
And this way, you can quite easily jump

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.000
between Pandas and Polars and start working

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.000
on the parts that you want to translate

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
to Polars first.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
One of the things that Jeroen already touched upon,

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
join the community.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:40.000
As you can see here, the community is big,

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:43.000
it's growing, and it's extremely helpful.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:45.000
I bet there's people that...

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:48.000
I remember talking with Richie one time

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:50.000
about people in the community,

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:53.000
about how even though Richie said he wrote Polars,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
there are still people in the community

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.000
that know how to use and make certain steps

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.000
sometimes better than he does,

00:25:58.000 --> 00:25:59.000
and I have the same thing.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:00.000
I wrote a book on it,

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
but there's still people in the chats in the community

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
that can help you out with problems so quickly,

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
and they know exactly the right methods to grab.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
The community is very experienced,

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:09.000
it's very open,

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.000
it's very active on Discord,

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:13.000
and I can definitely recommend to hop in there

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:16.000
to get to know the people there.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
So this is also the regression

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
that we were talking about earlier.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
It's also something I shared in the benchmark channel,

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
and there's a lot of people already

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.000
getting engaged with that,

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
and this is one of the responses of Richie to it,

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.000
mentioning that Gijs was also diving

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:34.000
on top of that regression

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:37.000
and had built a whole new way of running benchmarks

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:38.000
in an automated fashion

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:41.000
to prevent this from happening in the future,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:43.000
and there's people attaching to posts like that already,

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
and it generates a lot of buzz,

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
so it's always nice to notice.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
So, having had all these lessons

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:55.000
and having learned all these magical things

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:57.000
during our journey at Aliander,

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
ultimately it boiled down to a result, of course.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
We promised 98% reduction,

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
so we're going to have to come up with something.

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
So, the after situation.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:08.000
One net, one of those 35,000 nets.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Now it took four hours,

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
so that's a reduction of 20%.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
We did that with double the amount of work,

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
so instead of 25 samples,

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
we finally hit the target that the stakeholders set for us,

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:19.000
which is 50 samples.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.000
That's something from analysis.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
It turned out that the 50 samples is kind of a sweet spot

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
where it starts stabilizing out,

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.000
so that's what we needed to hit.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
Instead of the 500 gigabytes of RAM,

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:31.000
we can now do it in 40,

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:33.000
which is a 92% reduction.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
And, of course, it's now fully in Python.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
It's powered by Polars.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:41.000
So, this mostly helped the team

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:42.000
in trying to maintain the code.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
If you have to maintain both R scripts

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
that are connected to Python

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:47.000
through an RPy2 bridge,

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.000
that's just going to get hard to maintain at some point.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:54.000
So, at this point, it was just a fully Python file,

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
also running on a Docker

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
that you just have to have Python on

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
instead of all R packages as well.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:03.000
So, with this new setup,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
we were finally able to run a calculation

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
on the entire low-voltage grid,

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
which is those 35,000 nets.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.000
And, luckily, we did this at a lower cost than expected.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:18.000
So, where we got the target spend was $5,000,

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:22.000
we were able to run it in $3,500,

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
70% of our target.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
So, all of this was done even under the target spend.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.000
So, that boils us down to the big calculation

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:34.000
that if we had used the code

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
that we had two years before that,

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.000
it would have cost us 140K.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:41.000
And, sorry for AWS,

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:43.000
but now we're able to do it for 3.5K.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:46.000
So, ultimately, the big takeaway is that

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
we definitely came for the speed.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
We came looking for the performance,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:53.000
and that's definitely one of the things that pulled us in,

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
that helped us convince the team that this is a good idea.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
But, as we started building with it,

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.000
we just came to love it,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.000
and we ultimately stayed for the API.

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:07.000
So, to summarize,

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:10.000
start with show, don't tell.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.000
Don't let the numbers show more

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:14.000
than all the cool stories you can tell about Polars.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Like, the trust me bro is not going to do it for management,

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:19.000
so you need to back it up with some facts.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.000
You can get those by benchmarking.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Start early, start practically first thing.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
Like, if you're going to work with this,

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
okay, what's the status quo, what's the baseline?

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
And, just keep benchmarking.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
Every once in a while, after you add new features,

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:35.000
just run it again, see what's up.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.000
Definitely start using the Lazy API.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:41.000
The Eager API is brilliant to iteratively work

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
and see how you need to tweak your query

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:46.000
to get it to do what you want.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
But, ultimately, when you're putting it in your applications,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
you have to make it lazy.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.000
That makes it way faster.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.000
If you're trying to go too hard on the lazy thing,

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:57.000
that's not it either.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
So, if you do heavy calculations,

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.000
think about caching at some midpoints in between

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
to prevent double work.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.000
As you're doing that,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.000
you'll notice the fewer surprises in Polars.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:10.000
One of the reasons we came to love it.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:13.000
You can easily start small.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:16.000
You can swap between Pandas and Polars relatively easily

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:17.000
with just a couple of methods.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
So, you can just take out the parts

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:21.000
where you think it can make the most impact.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.000
Join a community.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:26.000
We would love to hear the stories.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:29.000
We would love to hear you guys share your successes.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
And, if you need help,

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:33.000
there's a community that's glad to help you out.

